    projectTitle:
      "We are running a campaign to fight the UK's restrictive speech laws and to produce research on the state of free speech in the UK.",
    projectDescription:
      "SPEAK UK (speakuk.org) is a non-partisan project led by Sam Glover, Duncan McClements, and Stella Tsantekidou, aiming to research and fight the UK's restrictive speech laws. We aim to launch a social media campaign in the style of last year’s successful campaign to ban the  American Bully XL dog in the UK. The basic modus operandi of the Bully XL campaign was to create a pipeline to identify cases where people had been seriously injured or killed by one of these dogs, get them viral on Twitter or other social media platforms, and create strong pressure on the government to ban the dog. Dr. Lawrence Newport (who we’ve met with several times) began this campaign in June 2023, and the dog was banned in February 2024. \n\nWe think we can do something similar. Duncan McClements, our Head of Research, is creating a pipeline to scrape court cases and news articles to identify people who have been arrested and/or convicted of speech-related offences that we think the public will be particularly sympathetic to (you can see some examples on our website at speakuk.org, in the Case Explorer). Sam and Stella will then push the cases on social media, on television (Stella is often invited on UK TV as a political pundit), in newspapers, and so on. We think we’re likely to get attention relatively quickly and make the issue of free speech in the UK much more salient, applying significant pressure to the Labour government.\n\nThere are a few points worth making here about why we think this is tractable and why we think it’s important (as well as why this will be significantly harder than the American XL Bully Campaign):\n\n- The American Bully campaign did not require new primary legislation (i.e. a law passed by the government in the House of Commons), it only required a Statutory Instrument, which is much easier for a government to do (and has a much lower opportunity cost). For this reason, we should be frank about the fact that this will be a much more difficult campaign than the Bully XL campaign.\n\n- That being said, we think there are reasons to be optimistic. Most notably, that the Reform UK Party is looking for policies like this to push on, as is potential future Conservative leader Robert Jenrick (current odds of him as next leader are around 44% on the betting markets), as is (to a lesser extent) current Conservative Party leader Kemi Badenoch. \n\n- After the successful Bully XL campaign, Lawrence Newport began a new campaign, Crush Crime, to tackle crime in the UK. This has been picked up by both Jenrick and Reform UK, who are eager to find policies that they can use to broaden their appeal. We think a similar thing could happen if/when speech goes viral. This could either result in Reform UK implementing our policies (or very similar ones) if they get into government, Jenrick/Badenoch implementing our policies if they get into government, or Labour feeling under pressure to adopt more liberal policies on free speech, even if those policies don’t go as far as we would like.\n\n- Importantly, our campaign is non-partisan. Most free speech campaigns in the UK (e.g. Free Speech Union) are extremely right-coded, and have no chance of appealing to a Labour government. The Free Speech Union has been keen on pushing anti-vaccine messages and is more interested in cancellations than legislation. We think we have a separate focus, are much more willing to work with all parties, and are much more likely to create broad support for liberal policies.\n\nWhy do we think this is important? 33 people per day are arrested for speech-related offences in the UK. It isn’t clear how many of these people are being arrested unjustly as opposed to genuine cases of sustained, targeted harassment. We think we can issue FOI requests to get a much better understanding of free speech in the UK, and to figure out which laws are the most egregious (and likely to result in genuinely unjust arrests for speech), and how we can repeal those laws. We do know that there are examples of people who have been arrested or convicted that we believe should not have been. \n\nExamples include:\n\n- Palestine Action supporters (note: including supporters who are not members) have been arrested (charged pending) for holding up signs that say things like ‘I support Palestine -Action’. This is possible because Palestine Action are a proscribed terrorist group in the UK, so any expression of support is illegal. \n- Lee Dunn, who was jailed for 8 weeks for reposting memes that were regarded as racist at the height of the Southport riots last year.\n- Maxie Allen was arrested and held for 11 hours (but not charged, after a 5 week investigation) for criticising their child’s school on WhatsApp in a private conversation.\n\nWe think that this is simply mad, and that it leaves the door open for future authoritarian governments to abuse the relevant laws to either proscribe groups they don’t like as terrorists or to arrest critics of the government for being grossly offensive.\n",
    backgroundQualifications:
      'At the moment, there are three of us. Sam Glover, Duncan McClements, and Stella Tsantekidou. We are all previous Emergent Ventures winners.\n\nI (Sam) am the director of SPEAK, and a former Research Analyst at the Forecasting Research Institute (I quit my job to pursue this campaign). I’m qualified to work on this campaign because I think I have very good connections that will allow me to get this stuff spreading quite widely (and quite quickly), I’m pretty familiar with how UK politics works, I have a strong research background that will lend itself to representing this issue honestly but effectively, and I’ll be capable of throwing together op-eds to explain why we think this is important (and have published in the Guardian before as well as on my personal blog, Samstack.io). I think I’m well-calibrated (I’m a Superforecaster) and think I’m able to reason well about which strategies are likely to work for this campaign, and I am pretty single-minded about winning rather than having some ulterior motive like becoming an MP or getting on television (there is one exception here - I would like to be able to leverage this campaign to do more campaigning in the future, especially on issues related to existential risk and animal welfare). \n\nI also just think I’m a strong generalist and quick learner when it makes sense in order to get things done - I put our website together using Cursor and some quick reading about how to use Javascript, I’m learning to edit video so that we can make Mamdani-style social media outputs, I was put on all sorts of work at FRI because I liked to try out new things (I was responsible for hiring, writing/editing work, running social science projects, etc.). I think I’ll adapt quickly to running a campaign.\n\nDuncan McClements is our Head of Research. He’s an undergraduate student in economics at Cambridge, a Research Fellow at the Centre for British Progress, and has conducted economic research for the Adam Smith Institute. His research output is extremely high quality - he’s been consistently fantastic at finding ways of getting data quickly that we thought would be extremely difficult to get. He has been responsible for much of the research behind Lawrence Newport’s previous campaigns, including Crush Crime and Looking for Growth.\n\nStella Tsantekidou is our campaign spokesperson. She is a political pundit in the UK who is often on national TV, she has >7,000 followers on Twitter, she knows the UK political system very well (with lots of connections), she has connections across the political spectrum, she has worked in lobbying in the UK parliament, she has worked as an aide to Labour politicians, and she headed the policy wing for a non-profit youth and justice government service provider in the UK. ',
