    projectTitle:
      'Increase compute available to find more solar system objects (including NEOs) hidden in astronomical databases using a custom, proven algorithm I’ve already implemented and support the development of a new algorithm capable of finding more objects currently under development.',
    projectDescription:
      'I am an independent researcher that develops algorithms that discover solar system objects hidden in databases of transient detections.  This award would support development and scaling of my custom implementation of HelioLinC which has the demonstrated ability to recover greater than 95% of objects from the Rubin Observatory’s DP0.3 simulation data and is actively finding new objects in the Isolated Tracklet File (ITF) produced by the Minor Planet Center (MPC) that the MPC itself did not find.\n\nHelioLinC “links” detections of solar system objects on different nights.  It essentially looks for “dots” in astronomical images that weren’t present at a location previously and aren’t there later and asks: “does this transient dot connect to other transient dots at other times with a specific orbit?”  If you can describe an orbit that passes through a bunch of dots at their observation times, you can validate that these dots belong to a singular moving object in the solar system – an asteroid most commonly.\n\nIn late 2025 or early 2026, Rubin Observatory will begin its Legacy Survey of Space and Time (LSST).  Rubin will produce the largest database of dots ever assembled.  This database will contain millions of asteroids, near-Earth objects (NEOs), trans-Neptunian objects (TNOs), interstellar objects (ISOs) and maybe even the hypothesized Planet Nine – but we need to pull them out of the data first.  \n\nWhile I will have access to Rubin’s database of dots, I do not currently have the compute necessary process data at the scale Rubin produces it.  If I receive this award, the most important thing I will do is purchase new computers to enable Rubin-scale data processing.  Additionally, I currently process data in the MPC’s ITF (the central database of unidentified dots), but will be able to do a deeper search and find more objects with the additional compute.  I’m particularly interested in the potential to deepen my search for NEOs which might pose a threat to Earth and are some of the most computationally expensive objects to recover.\n\nI am also in the process of creating a new linking algorithm which I’m calling HyperLinC-1 (Inverse HyperLinC).  This new algorithm builds on all the things I’ve learned developing HelioLinC over the years to enable searches over a longer duration but with fewer same-night detections.  HelioLinC currently requires at least two dots per night to recover an object; HyperLinC-1 would only require one.  This allows you to find objects that are only detected once per night.  Unlike my HelioLinC implementation, which is already fully implemented and finding new objects, HyperLinC-1 is still speculative.  But I’ve already started building the algorithm and have evidence from results to date that the capabilities will exceed that of HelioLinC.\n\nI currently support my independent research through part-time non-astronomy work (retail web stuff) and personal savings.  With this funding I will be able to acquire the computing resources that will enable increased object discovery and dedicate more time to moving object research.',
    backgroundQualifications:
      'I’m qualified to work on solar system object detection because I already detect a lot of new solar system objects with HelioLinC – custom software I’ve written for that purpose [1].  The Minor Planet Center keeps track of how many objects contributors “identify” – that is: link dots together with other dots in a database of dots to confirm the identification of a new object.  In 2024 I was in the top 10 of ITF-ITF linkers (the category which results in newly designated objects).  I am among the last of the contributors to look at the data (due to professional institutions having live database feeds while I currently have a snapshot), which leads me to believe I might be finding at least some of the harder to discover objects.\n\nIn addition to actually identifying new objects, I have also made contributions to Rubin Observatory’s search tools [2].  Starting in 2026, Rubin will use a different implementation of HelioLinC than mine (there are 2-3 variants of HelioLinC in the community which differ fairly significantly) to search for new objects.  Rubin has adopted my “RR clustering phase space” as one of its search techniques.  This is one thing that my algorithm and Rubin’s have in common, but there are many more that set us apart (especially in the very near and very distant object category) and suggests that our separate techniques will not fully overlap in the objects they find.\n\nFinally, I attend and contribute at professional astronomy conferences.  Just this past month I’ve presented a poster on a HelioLinC optimization that reduces compute time requirements for near-Earth objects – among the most compute intensive objects to find due to their non-linearly varying heliocentric distance in time requiring more hypotheses than other bodies in the solar system [3].\n\nOh, I guess I should mention my academic background too.  I have a B.S. in Physics and a M.S. in Aerospace Engineering with an emphasis on Astrodynamics.\n\n1: https://minorplanetcenter.net/mpcops/documentation/identifications/stats/2024/ – click on ‘ITF-ITF’\n2: https://github.com/heliolinx/heliolinx – ctrl+F: Engebreth\n3: https://www.benengebreth.org/dynamic-sky/implied-orbits-and-sad-tracklets/Finding_more_NEOS_with_HelioLinC_and_SAD_tracklet_rejection.pdf\n',
