    projectTitle:
      'Create a permanent, public, and computable foundation of biological knowledge by building an AI-powered engine that automatically standardizes and curates the world’s biological datasets—past, present, and future.',
    projectDescription:
      "#Executive summary\nBiology produces enormous datasets with the potential to transform medicine, yet most remain functionally invisible due to poor organization and inconsistent metadata. Covalent.bio solves this by using AI to fully standardize entire public repositories—at scale, with high quality, and cost-effectively. This unique capability allows the instant discovery and creation of proprietary, high-value, machine learning–ready training data that model-building groups are urgently seeking—unlocking Covalent’s first major commercial opportunity.\nThe ultimate vision is to make biology predictable. Covalent is strategically positioned to move systematically up the value chain—starting with decision-support tools (ML models) for drug discovery and ultimately advancing to the high-end by developing their own therapeutic pipeline. In doing so, they aim to not only accelerate the pace of biomedical breakthroughs but also to own differentiated, high-value intellectual property at every stage.\n\n#We are panning for gold while sitting atop a goldmine\nOver the past decade, biology has become a data science. Researchers generate exabytes of genomic, proteomic, and clinical data annually. In theory, we're living in a golden age of biomedical research.\nIn practice, we're drowning. The vast majority of public biological data is disorganized, poorly documented, and functionally unusable. It's buried across hundreds of repositories, described in inconsistent formats, plagued by errors, with vague labels and missing metadata. These datasets are invisible to most scientists—and useless to AI.\nThis is not a small technical annoyance. It is a structural failure—a silent, systemic breakdown at the heart of modern science. Meanwhile, thousands of scientists and machine learning engineers are locked out of discovery.\n\n#Covalent’s solution\nCovalent is building a centralized, AI-powered metadata engine—one that automatically ingests, standardizes, and continuously updates metadata across all public biological datasets. This system turns every public dataset into a findable, trustworthy, machine-readable resource from the moment it is published.\nNow imagine this for every public dataset in existence. Scientists could find relevant studies in seconds using natural language. Flawed metadata would be automatically flagged. Machine learning models could train on integrated datasets spanning multiple modalities. Discovery itself would accelerate, raising all boats.\n\n#A market starving of ML training data\nCovalent has conducted a comprehensive market research covering nearly 200 model-building companies/groups. Below is a very brief summary of only one of the identified market clusters.\n📁Transcriptomics (Gene Expression)\nTechnology: bulk and single-cell RNA sequencing.\nPreprocessing: map RNA-seq reads to transcriptome, quantify gene counts or TPM, normalize across samples (e.g. combat for batch effects, log-transform).\nGroups & models:\n- Lantern Pharma’s RADR\n- BenevolentAI\n- Scailyte’s disease pattern finder & Immunai’s immune AI\n\nWhat becomes apparent is that the same preprocessing tasks serve multiple groups across industry and academia. This redundancy means Covalent can add huge value: rather than each group reinventing the wheel, a specialized pipeline can do it once and serve many.\n\n\n#Making biology predictable: gradually, then suddenly\nOur technical vision enables a disruptive go-to-market strategy that is designed to create differentiated, high-value intellectual property at every stage.\n\n1️⃣The metadata layer\nCovalent’s immediate focus is on standardizing and enriching the metadata of the entire NCBI's SRA and GEO. This is a technically tractable, capital-efficient, and high-leverage starting point. \nDelivery: 3 months\nTarget customers: 3rd party platforms (e.g., NASA GeneLab, Kepler AI, FutureHouse, Mantle Bio, Benchling, Latch.bio, Rancho, Elucidata, BioTuring, Synthesize.bio)\nRevenue potential: small ($50k-$100k) \n\n2️⃣The provider of ML training data\nCovalent’s enriched, standardized metadata allows instant dataset discovery. Our primary commercial focus is the \"virtual cell\" opportunity. \nDelivery: 6 months\nTarget customers: Chan-Zuckerberg Initiative and Arc Institute. Also, companies like Insilico Medicine, Owkin, CytoReason, and Recursion selling decision-support systems to pharma R&D.\nRevenue potential: medium ($500k-$5M) \n\n3️⃣The model builder\nThe unparalleled datasets assembled through Covalent’s public pipeline will become a unique asset for training their own proprietary machine learning models. By moving up the value chain from data provider to insight generator, Covalent will address critical challenges in drug discovery. \nDelivery: 24 months\nTarget customers: big pharma and large biotechs running drug development pipelines (e.g., Shift Biosciences)\nRevenue potential: medium ($1M-$20M) \n\n4️⃣CovalentTx\nDelivery: 3-5 years\nRevenue potential: large ($100M-$1B)\n\n\n",
    backgroundQualifications:
      "#About Nicholas Schaum\nMy work is driven by a single goal: to keep as many people as possible healthy for as long as possible. Fifteen years ago, I began by dissecting individual molecular pathways in ageing biology, hoping to prevent disease onset. But I soon realized that generating community‑wide resources would amplify impact far more. That led me to convene over 100 researchers to build Tabula Muris Senis, the first organism‑wide, single‑cell atlas of ageing, in partnership with the CZ Biohub.\n\nI then co‑founded Rejuvenome, a $70 million proto-FRO mapping how rejuvenation strategies affect the ageing process across the body. From scratch, we assembled a dedicated team of twelve, designed a seven‑year roadmap, and processed tens of thousands of samples in our first year alone.\n\nWhen Rejuvenome was abruptly halted, I stepped back and recognized a deeper bottleneck: data generation now outstrips our ability to organize and interpret it. At a FutureHouse workshop, I realized that machine learning could bridge that gap—so long as we first make every dataset machine‑ready. Today, my mission is to build that foundation: an AI‑driven platform that transforms fragmented biological data into a unified resource, empowering researchers everywhere to accelerate discovery and improve human health.\n\n\n#About Jorge Bastos\nI bring a unique blend of technical expertise and strategic product leadership. For over two decades, I’ve led the development of software and data products that empower people—from children learning maths to families managing debt. At TotallyMoney, I joined pre-launch and helped grow the platform to over 5 million users. I built the first machine learning model for credit card eligibility, transforming how people managed their finances. More importantly, it made a real difference—helping people under financial stress make better decisions. I'm now applying that same mission-driven approach to the biosciences: building infrastructure that empowers both human and AI scientists.\n\nCovalent.bio, co-founded with Nick Schaum, is my response to a core bottleneck in biology: AI can't fulfill its promise until biological data is clean, discoverable, and machine-readable. The ultimate aim is to make biology predictable—enabling simulated interventions, faster drug discovery, and the precise design of biological systems.\n\nCovalent is designed to be an open, enduring public-good infrastructure with a sustainable path to scale. We are at an inflection point in biology. With the right infrastructure, we can unlock a Cambrian explosion of discovery. Covalent is designed to be that foundation. And I am committed—intellectually, emotionally, and professionally—to seeing it through.",
