    projectTitle:
      'Golem Labs: An AI safety startup that automates creation of defensive tools like AI control and cyber ranges.',
    projectDescription:
      "Short AI development timelines mean governments and labs may lack sufficient time to implement comprehensive safety measures, making defensive mitigations critical for preventing AI x-risk. We need practical defensive tools deployable alongside advanced AI systems. AI control involves monitoring and intervention mechanisms that detect unauthorized frontier AI actions and automatically intervene using weaker AI models. Cyber ranges are simulated environments replicating real-world infrastructure where we can safely test AI offensive capabilities and our defenses. Taken together, such defenses could be \"defense-dominant\": weaker AI systems with the right tools could contain even moderately superintelligent adversaries.\n.\nDespite their critical importance, the field is constrained: I estimate that fewer than 50 researchers globally work on AI control and defensive cyber solutions. The UK AISI Control Team lead estimates we need thousands of control settings to test approaches, yet each takes weeks to months to develop. These include shutdown triggers, sandbox configurations, and deceptive alignment detection. I’ve seen firsthand how training new researchers can take years: research taste, defensive cybersecurity, and engineering take time to get right. \n.\nMany AI existential risk pathways involve rogue systems compromising critical infrastructure through cyber attacks. A single escaped AI could cascade through interconnected systems, replicating itself across datacentres and critical infrastructure and ultimately leading to a loss of control scenario. Robust control settings and cyber ranges let labs test models before deployment and let labs and governments program defenses into critical infrastructure like defence infrastructure, datacentres and government infrastructure. Even partial coverage dramatically improves our odds, as each additional setting closes potential escape routes for a misaligned rogue AI.\n.\nGolem Labs will create AI agents that augment human labour to scale production of defensive tools by an order of magnitude. The name draws from the Golem of Prague, the legendary defender of Prague’s Jews from attack. Just as the Golem was an example of augmentation of human defences, Golem Labs’s research program develops agents that transform specifications into production-ready defensive tools. We'll establish ourselves as a nonprofit, likely transitioning to a public benefit corporation for SAFE investment as we demonstrate traction.\n.\nThe implementation will explore several potential approaches: scaffolded agents using Inspect and ControlArena with procedural generation parameters; finetuning open-source models on quality cyber ranges and control settings to create more; and RL pipelines for cyber range generation. Initial work requires $25,000: $10,000 compute, $15,000 wages. This enables SF Bay relocation to find a technical co-founder. If unsuccessful within three months, I'll return remaining funds. As a UKAISI founding member who ran the world's largest AI safety research program (nearly 200 people, nearly 12,000 person-hours), I think I have the necessary context, knowledge and ability to build but need dedicated time for experiments and team building, as my current AISI responsibilities demand full focus.\n.\nGolem Labs targets a specific, tractable niche. Organizations like Redwood and AISI lack capacity for engineering-first automation, being rightly focused on core research. Labs are devoting capacity to capability augmentation. But humans have successfully built control settings and cyber ranges, and AI has proven effective augmenting software engineering. If successful, these could be sold - revenue would come from labs, government contracts, and critical infrastructure providers.\n.\nOptimistically, mass-produced control settings and cyber ranges will contain dangerous AIs during early deployment, buying years for ultimate alignment while providing government warning shots. We'd catch rogue behavior before escalation, studying misalignment in controlled environments. The median outcome: significantly increased defensive tool production advancing AI control science, with partial lab adoption buying months for alignment. Even this represents substantial improvement over current trajectories.",
    backgroundQualifications:
      "My track record suggests I can execute ambitious AI safety projects at scale. I led AISI's $3m evaluations bounty: nearly 200 researchers, 141 evaluations, 12,000 hours of work on autonomous replication and safety sabotage evals. This worked because I continually ratcheted up the ambition, but also paid attention to detail and what the field needed.I’ve also led other projects like AISI’s $2.5m human baselines project. At the Bletchley Park AI Safety Summit in 2023, I led on creating AI risk demos for Dario Amodei, Elon Musk and others. I managed the delivery of the world's most comprehensive report on [a specific AI risk area - cannot say more] for Western government stakeholders. Earlier, as a student I scaled Raise (a malaria fundraising charity) from $16K to $140K across 11 universities. \nPattern across my career: I join early-stage organizations and help them scale effectively. Joined AISI as employee ~20 (now 250), where I served as Technical Programme Manager for the world's first government autonomy risk testing. Joined Simon Institute (International AI governance orgnansiation) as first employee, scaled from 3 to 6 people and $100K to $1.2M funding. Won the Apart AI Safety Hackathon (https://apartresearch.com/project/antimidas-building-commercially-viable-agents-for-alignment-dataset-generation). Each time, I've had to quickly model what the AI safety field needs, build it, then adapt when reality proves my models wrong. I think I’ve gotten a lot better at this over time and am excited to try this with Golem.\n.\nMy revealed preferences demonstrate commitment—I took a 50% salary cut to work in my current AI safety role. And now I’m willing to take a risk in leaving a fairly central and prestigious job to build something new in the service of impact. My hypothesis is that scaling defensive AI safety tool production by >10x has higher marginal impact than incremental improvements to government testing that I could do. This could be wrong, but the downside is bounded (returning grant money if I can't find a co-founder) while upside could be significant (comprehensive defensive coverage could end up buying years for alignment).\n.\nEvidence of my ability comes from people who've observed my work directly. A few people include Jasmine Wang (OpenAI), Jay Bailey (UK AISI), Henry Sleight (Constellation). Please ask me before reaching out for references - I will check in by courtesy with these people but expect this to be fine. ",
