    projectDescription:
      'Medical imaging tools are currently gated behind hospitals, permissions, and significant costs. This imposes a severe bottleneck on how often people scan themselves. The high-performance tools are too big and bulky. The portable tools are low-performance.\n\nThis deficiency manifests in a whole range of problems people face outside of the hospital. The standard of care is to deal with each without any real feedback from the body. We don’t think of these as “problems for medical imaging”, because we are not used to having imaging capabilities outside the hospital. To pick a few very specific and narrow examples out of several, each of which could be handled by continuously monitoring the abdominal region.: predicting fecal and urinary incontinence events [1][2][3], stomach acid levels for people with GERD [4], precisely estimating ovulation time for fertility [5].\n\nBesides the impact on individual health, this technology will have important implications for medical research. Nobody has scanned the body’s internals at scale for millions of people from all over the world and assembled a large (tall+wide) scale dataset. Wide-spread use of our scanning technology will generate data that can advance both our practice of medicine, and our understanding of human physiology.\n\nWe wish to make medical imaging ubiquitous and frictionless as smartphone cameras have become. Of the three main medical imaging modalities, X-rays are carcinogenic under repeated exposure, MRI scanners require large magnetic fields and are hard to miniaturize, leaving only ultrasound as the ideal solution. We are thus motivated to an ultrasound imaging device with a frictionless user experience which is also economical to manufacture at scale.\n\nWe are not just making the trivial claim that we will make ultrasound imaging cheaper by mass-manufacturing the hardware. We are developing ultrasound imaging technology in a wearable patch form factor, that can leverage commercially available off the shelf parts which are mass manufactured for other applications which makes our devices cheaper. It is a fundamental improvement in architecture which provides superior performance while using components available in the market. Canonical ultrasound imaging needs a skilled operator. Our hardware would make it trivial to aim the ultrasound device in the correct direction. The AI layer on top would extract the relevant biomarker from the image without any further human intervention. This would enable anyone to use the device without training.\n\nHere are the things we’ve done so far:\n    1. Tested the physics assumptions experimentally with an experiment.\n    2. Built a simulated digital twin, for the core sensing hardware and the critical software elements based on reasonable + explicit physics assumptions.\n    3. Discussed with doctors and potential/putative users to discover the right first application, and devised a staged roll-out strategy for the sequence in which applications will be enabled by our platform technology.\n    4. Estimated SWAP-C for a first version of a HW device at moderate scale (100k units). Size: Cell-phone size, Weight: 200g - 250g, Power: 1 week battery life, Cost: $350. Please keep these details confidential. We will disclose these details publicly when the time is right.\n    \n    Our next step is to build a prototype that produces an image, and demonstrates our claims of radically improving the size/cost/power vs performance tradeoff.\n    \n    [1] Patients consider incontinence to be worse than death: 10.1001/jamainternmed.2016.4362\n    \n    [2] Old paper which proves clinical efficacy of our device for urinary incontinence: [10.1016/s0022-5347(01)68141-2](https://doi.org/10.1016/s0022-5347(01)68141-2)\n    \n    [3] Paper shows that it’s feasible to measure rectal and bladder volume in a single measurement: [10.1007/s10396-023-01339-2](https://doi.org/10.1007/s10396-023-01339-2)\n    \n    [4] Standard of care for GERD has no feedback on the stomach contents: [10.5009/gnl16615](https://doi.org/10.5009/gnl16615). Our device can help patients by giving them live feedback, making lifestyle modifications much easier.\n    \n    [5] Ultrasound imaging can track the ovulation cycle in women [10.1080/09513590.2018.1522297](https://doi.org/10.1080/09513590.2018.1522297). Continuous monitoring can help accurately predict the ovulation cycles and improve the odds of normal and assisted reproductive technology.',
    backgroundQualifications:
      'There are two of us working on this project: Siva Swaminathan and Subhash Sadhu (me). We’ll talk about the both of us.\n\nDeveloping this device needs expertise in photonics, electronic hardware design and manufacturing, imaging and reconstruction algorithms, and AI. Developing this needs tight collaboration between people who have deep expertise. Between the two of us, we have the combination of physics, hardware engineering, math & AI expertise to build this technology.\n\nI (Subhash) developed semiconductor ICs for 3D Time-of-Flight imaging systems at Texas Instruments, including machine vision and camera/LiDAR development for AMZN robotics and DJI. I hold 10 granted USPTO patents related to this work [1], which were key to TI’s strategic dominance in 3D ToF imaging for many years. I designed subsystems within ICs, and also designed electronics and optics of full systems which went into manufactured products. I did Masters in Computational Imaging at MIT Media Lab where I designed the hardware and image reconstruction algorithms for LIDARs which can see around corners[1]. I worked at an early-stage startup, and developed long-range Silicon Photonics based LIDAR. I solved many system level problems, and developed robust investor demos of the integrated system with hardware which was anything but robust.\n\nSiva was enamored with signal processing while studying Electrical Engineering in undergrad. He obtained a PhD in theoretical physics to scratch his childhood itch, but soon returned to his penchant for mathematics applied at the interface of physics and algorithms.  Following his PhD, he worked on computer vision and 3d computational geometry applied to robotics at Vicarious AI. Recently, he has been an AI researcher at Google DeepMind, building intelligent agents that can leverage world models to solve problems efficiently through planning and reasoning. He has multiple peer-reviewed publications in physics and AI [2] and several patents [2] for developing key technology in each of his roles.\n\nThe both of us have a complementary skillset and this helps us take responsibility for each of our areas of expertise. Together, we can build this.\n\n[1] https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=BZEhxl8AAAAJ&hl=en&oi=ao\n\n[2] https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=oDVFD5oAAAAJ&hl=en&oi=ao',
