    projectDescription:
      "Airborne disease is bad [citation needed]. Most of our current tools for prevention make it the individual's responsibility: vaccines, masks, and testing. As the recent pandemic showed, people hate doing these things and will often refuse.\n\nBuilt-environment interventions for the prevention of airborne disease are desirable because they only require convincing a building owner to make a decision once, rather than convincing every individual everywhere to make a decision, whether daily (masks), regularly (tests), or yearly (vaccines).\n\nFar-UVC is one of the most promising built-environment interventions we know about for the pathogen-agnostic prevention of airborne disease. Our best guess is that, at worst, it is about as good as the next-most-cost effective intervention (portable air cleaners) in reducing airborne disease transmission, and may be 10 or 100 times more effective.\nFar-UVC currently faces limited adoption, partly due to its high cost. A high-quality, long-lasting far-UVC lamp costs ~$2000, and is largely marketed to institutional customers. Unfortunately, institutional customers tend to be fairly conservative, and are hesitant to spend large sums of money on new technologies. \n\nIn April, we started Aerolamp, a company focused on producing user-friendly, low-cost open-source far-UVC lamps. We use the highest-quality components and are confident that our product will be performant for up to 5 years of daily use, with a current price tag of $500. We’re the most cost-effective option on the market by about a factor of three, and at high volume we expect to be able to drop that price by another factor of three.\n\nCurrently, we are selling 3D printed ‘development kit’ versions of the lamps in small volumes, lowering the barrier to access with the hope of smoothing the path to mass adoption of far-UVC. However, we need to transition to a fully ‘productized’ version soon–this means fully updating the current version of the Aerolamp to a mass-producible version which complies with all relevant product standards.\n\nThe project is also open source, and we would appreciate contributors with experience in high voltage electronics, rf, UVC, and firmware experience.\n\n\n\n",
