      "I could make use of as much or as little money as you'll give me. Here's a few ranges:  *$5-10k* I could develop a functional prototype with off-the-shelf, consumer electronics. I think the best way to achieve this would be to buy an MSI Vector 16 HX AI 400 Gaming Laptop, with an RTX 5080M GPU (~$3.3-3.7k in the UK). This is the cheapest laptop with the most powerful mobile NVIDIA GPU one can buy today (RVC needs CUDA). I would remove the screen, keyboard, trackpad, and the rest of the case. I would rehouse the remaining components in a 3D printed enclosure I will develop. I have access to a 3D printer for initial designs, and I'll use a professional 3D printer for the final version. I will pair this with a head-mounted microphone, and a small speaker attached to the unit by a spiral cable, able to clip where the user pleases (including to the unit itself).  This seems the best option for a lower budget because it will be the easiest to get working, and avoid the need to buy additional components. Since I'd be shucking a laptop, the battery system would already be built in, and I wouldn't have to worry about designing a cooling solution. The form factor of the resulting prototype would be fairly large, however, and I would be unable to prototype additional components since it would all be soldered to the motherboard.  The logic behind, on a limited budget, going for a 50-series GPU is that I want to make sure that the prototype has the best chance of working effectively. I suspect a 40-series GPU would be sufficient, but I don't want to blow a limited budget on an underpowered chip. Efficiency could come at later stages of development. This would allow me to get something together which works which I could then use to attract further funding (public or private).  Any money left over from hardware would go towards my own labour costs. Without this, I will have to work more hours elsewhere to keep a roof over my head, slowing the project down. In addition to hardware considerations, I would need to set up a lean Linux image which can headlessly boot straight into the model, lighting an external LED to indicate the device is ready for use.  *$10-15k* With a bit more money, I could be more ambitious in my design, because I would have more money to test different components, account for mistakes, and be able to apply more time to development. In this range, instead of shucking a laptop, I would buy industrial parts. For example, an MXM GPU module like this, once it is available: https://www.aetina.com/products-detail.php?i=694 This is the form factor of GPU used in embedded and industrial systems. This sort of prototyping is important in order to find out the cheapest viable chips for the device.  This would lead to a more compact and (ironically) cheaper prototype, since I wouldn't be repurposing a laptop-sized motherboard. But it would take me longer to develop, so some more of the money would be used to apply more time (still part-time) to development. I would need to work out cooling, might need to wrestle with BIOS setups, and would need to build a battery system. With more design control, I could add more external information. Perhaps a battery indicator, or buttons to change parameters on the model (e.g. sensitivity to background noise). In this scenario, I would also have more time to work on the underlying model. With some time to apply myself, I think I could manage to switch out the pitch detection algorithm, play more with ONNX models, etc.  *$15k-50k* At this scale of funding, two things become possible.  First, I would be able to dedicate myself full-time to this project, for something in the order of a few months to a year, depending on the exact grant. I live in a small, shared house. Currently, I would need to regularly pack prototype components away every day, as I would be working in common spaces. With this amount of funding, I could take out a (still modest) tenancy on a place for myself, ensuring that I have somewhere (a spare room, a corner of a living room, etc.) which I can use as a permanent workshop space. Alternatively, I could rent office space, but since I need somewhere to live anyway, getting my own place would be more cost-effective. ($1000-1100/month for where I live.)  Secondly, I'm going to hit hurdles from time to time. At this level of funding, I would be able to pay for short bits of contracting work in order to help me in such situations. Perhaps I can't quite work out an aspect of the 3D-printing design, or I have an issue getting the BIOS to recognise the MXM module. Without this level of funding I could work it out eventually, either through trial and error or through informally reaching out to external experts (even just posting on forums). But development would be much quicker if I could bring temporary expertise onto the project, accelerating my timeline.  *$50k-100k* So far my focus has been on building a functional prototype that I can use to attract follow-on funding for a production-ready device. With significantly more funding from you, I could move faster towards that end goal and tackle areas beyond my current skillset. This range of funding may not quite get me to production, but it would enable me to not worry about funding for longer, and drastically accelerate development. This would be very helpful, because the technology for this product to exist is readily available, and someone is going to get there first eventually.  On the technical side, I would bring in experienced engineers to refine the voice conversion model for whispered speech. It already works well, but improvements could make the output even clearer. Model inference and the secondary software (the OS, etc.) could also likely be optimised, reducing GPU requirements, cutting hardware costs, and speeding up system boot time. I could also get help finalising a production-ready design, and developing relationships with suppliers and a factory. But whether I would reach this stage in this budget would depend on how the prior steps work out, any unforeseen factors, etc.  On the regulatory side, I could start generating the evidence needed for medical certification. This means engaging with clinicians and piloting the device with multiple users, not just myself. The additional funding would allow me to build multiple prototypes for these trials, collect structured data, and attend relevant medical conferences and the like to build relationships with industry professionals.  The upper range of ACX funding would let me not only dedicate myself to the project full-time, but hire collaborators for extended periods and move through the early stages far faster, from technical development to hiring a patent lawyer. While I have no ambitions to be a rockstar founder, getting out into the world early on (meeting clinicians, showing the device in action, building credibility) would set the foundation for scaling and adoption.   NOTE: It is likely that I would incur taxes in receiving your grant. I am yet to establish this venture as a legal entity, but, if I did, I understand that I would pay less or perhaps even zero tax on the grant in the UK. I think it's good for people to pay their taxes, but I would nonetheless speak to a tax professional first to make sure I am not needlessly losing money, and take action accordingly to maximise the impact of your contribution. I hope you will forgive me for not totally wrapping my head around this aspect yet, but I don't want to count chickens before they have hatched.",
